    ETA Plots

    Kyle Baron

    2018-11-02

    eta.Rmd

    Set up

    library(pmplots)
library(dplyr)

data <- pmplots_data_id()

    A good workflow is to create a character vector of your etas and their names.

    etas <- c("ETA1//ETA-CL", "ETA2//ETA-VC", "ETA3//ETA-KA")

etas
    ## [1] "ETA1//ETA-CL" "ETA2//ETA-VC" "ETA3//ETA-KA"

    Note that very frequently, ETA plots come back as a list of plots, one for each ETA. In our examples, we’ll use the cowplot package to arrange the plots into a grid.

    We’ll make a special version of plot_grid that will make the piping a little smoother

    library(cowplot)

grid_plot <- function(x) plot_grid(plotlist=x)

    ETA histogram

    eta_hist(data,etas) %>% grid_plot()
    ## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

    ETA Pairs

    eta_pairs(data,etas)
    ## Loading required namespace: GGally

    ETA versus categorical variable

    eta_cat(data, x = "STUDYc", y = etas) %>% grid_plot()
